                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Triceps Lateral Heads</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30725681/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">triceps muscle</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> covers the back of your upper arm, running from the shoulder to the elbow. It consists of three distinct parts, known as heads. The lateral head is one the outer portion of the tricep, farthest away from the body.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Your lateral head is only significantly active when working against resistance. The function of the lateral head of the triceps is to extend the elbow to straighten the arm. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">That is the primary movement when performing the cable tricep pushdown. This makes it one of the best </span><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/lateral-head-tricep-exercises" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">lateral head tricep exercises</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></p><h3><b>Triceps Medial Heads</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The medial head of the triceps represents the inner portion of the triceps. Like the lateral head, it also originates from the humerus, or upper arm bone. It inserts into your ulna or forearm. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The only function of the medial head of the triceps is elbow extension. When you perform the cable tricep pushdown, this head is engaged.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Compared to the lateral and long, the medial head is active in all forms of elbow extension. It’s most active when the shoulder is about 90 degrees of elevation.</span></p><h3><b>Triceps Long Heads </b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The long head of the triceps is the inner portion of the horseshoe shape, closest to the body. It differs from the other two heads because it has a different point of origin. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This head’s muscle fibers originate on the shoulder blade (scapula), just below the shoulder socket. It runs down the back of the upper arm alongside the other two heads. All three heads combine to cross the elbow joint and attach to the ulna.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Its attachment to the shoulder blade means that the long head of the triceps also stabilizes the shoulder. However, its primary function is to work with the other two heads in extending the elbow.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">At 0 degrees of shoulder elevation, the </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29503079/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">long head</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is shown to be the most active. More specifically, at around 35 degrees of elbow flexion, it has a maximum voluntary contraction of around 15% MVC.</span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
